color=#00CC00><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bmrcliffordsenglishclasses.showUserPublicProfile?gid=tcliffdawg>tcliffdawg</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 4<br> <font color=#00CC00>(2/3/03 11:47:01 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fmrcliffordsenglishclassesfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=14.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Themes in Huck Finn</span><hr size=1> Many dim-witted readers believe that the book Huck Finn is an anti-slavery book. However the book was written 20 years after slaves were freed. Think about what other ideas are communicated in this book. Based on what you've read thus far, what do you think is another theme or idea that Twain communicates to his readers? Describe your answer and defend it by referring to at least one scene from the novel. (Your posting is worth 15 points, and should be at least one complete and thorough paragraph.) In addition to posting your answer to this message board, e-mail your work to your favorite American Lit -- Honors teacher at tcliffor@monterey.k12.ca.us <br>
